<!-- image_size: width=1655, height=2339 --> # A Design Case Study in the Effectiveness of Generative Models R. Spencer Steenblik RA, Omar Dib PhD, Jonathan Hill Indiana University Bloomington, Wenzhou- Kean University, Indiana University ## Abstract Similar to the slow food movement, there may be a need to take in, and be more aware of every step throughout the design process. "Slow Design can indeed have a positive impact on wellbeing." In another context, Minsky discusses training an AI model and states "slow learning... smoothes away uncertainties due to noise". Today with generative AI tools able to ideate and visualize incestly toward an accelerated design process, we run the risk of getting caught in a place where design happens in front of the designer more than through the designer. Minsky elaborates "it will at last become economical to match human beings in real time with really large machines. This means that we can work toward programming what will be, in effect, "thinking aids." In the years to come, we expect that these manmachine systems will share, and perhaps for a time be dominant, in our advance toward the development of "artificial intelligence." This article considers workflows for several AI models in collaboration with designers to tackle a real world design problem. We will spend time comparing and contrasting how these models

be dominant, in our advance toward the development of "artificial intelligence." This article considers workflows for several AI models in collaboration with designers to tackle a real world design problem. We will spend time comparing and contrasting how these models impact design workflows, making observations along the way about enhancing features and again where fidelity is lost. We will include Neural Style Transfer(NST) (an older generative AI model) which isn't as streamlined nor high fidelity. We will briefly discuss some relevent technicalities of this older model in order to illucidate opportunities of an older model with lower fidelity than the current state of the art. The lower quality, sketchy output creates ambiguity for the designer to interpret. Potentially allowing the imagination and the designers intuition to play a larger role than with some of the newer models. Working with machine learning neural style transfer (NST) can allow the designers to consider possibilities humanity may not otherwise allow ourselves to imagine. This project tests this hypothisis. Perhaps we should linger in the "man- machine system" paradigm a little longer even if we are able to go further? ## Keywords Hybrid Intelligence; Cognitive Prosthetic; Machine Learning; Schematic Design; sublime; Neural Style Transfer; Neural Networks; AI in Design; Humanity; design workflow; design exploration; early design stage; ## 1. <!-- image_size: width=1655, height=2339 --> This work outlines an approach to using neural style transfer (NST) in a novel way as a part of the early architectural design process. We seek to use the tool in a way unintended by its creators, for results different from many examples or use cases. (Liu et al 2021) (Liu 2021)(Wang 2021) The work presented herein attempts to blur the lines between architectural design, story telling, digital media, computer science and other disciplines. The objective of the effort is to inspire humanity toward a brighter future through imagining and instantiating possible futures. Divergent from many other documented use cases within the design process, this use case of NST focuses on a more intuitive, iterative, feedback loop between designer and the computational process. (Fig 3) We attempt to achieve a guided vision, possibly beyond the potential conceptions of the designer in unaided circumstances to conceive of the outcomes, or potential design schemes. Built on several speculative architectural workshops, art exhibitions, and design studios at Tongji DigitalFUTURES, FutureLab Shanghai, Longxi Art Museum, and Wenzhou- Kean University, respectively, this paper seeks ontological uncertainty between the artist and a cognitive prosthetic using the machine learning technologies of a convolutional neural network (CNN), and more specifically NST in the early design phase for novel design solutions. The collection of NST compositions represented in this article are primarily possible futures. One might ask about the merit of compositions that do not seem to be feasible or viable as constructed architecture. Yet these blue sky explorations can exist only digitally, or possibly become a part of humanity's built reality at some point in the future. Regardless of their final instantiation, by very conception, these possibilities become exactly that, a possibility, otherwise impossible. This paper will first outline our process. Afterward consider some of the lineage from which this work springs and the potential power of the speculative world building process. (Young 2020) Next we will consider the low hanging fruit of instantiating these places at least virtually in the metaverse and/or through VR, animation as a way to solidify their somewhat timid present reality. ## 2. Background Recent advances in Artificial Intelligence have demonstrated the ability of Deep Learning models such as Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) to generate artistic imageries by extracting and recombining the content of an image and a style. This process of applying different styles to an image

Intelligence have demonstrated the ability of Deep Learning models such as Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) to generate artistic imageries by extracting and recombining the content of an image and a style. This process of applying different styles to an image content via a CNN architecture is usually referred to as Neural Style Transfer (NST) (Gatys et al., 2016). Due to its visually plausible results, the research in NST has amassed a significant amount of attention and effort from academic and industry practitioners. Various novel approaches have been proposed to improve the original NST architecture or extend it to cope with new application settings. In addition, many successful industrial applications have been developed and begun to deliver commercial benefits. For example, in social communication, NST applications have aided people in creating artworks and sharing their art paintings on social media platforms, which can be regarded as a new form of social communication. In that regard, Prisma<sup>1</sup> and deeparteffects<sup>2</sup> have been among the digital applications that have successfully provided NST as a service for many users. Similarly, in the contribution of (Reimann et al., 2018), authors introduced "MaeSTrO," a novel mobile application that facilitates a creative and localized style transfer editing process. Beyond social communication, NST has been a precious assisted tool for painters and designers. Nowadays, NST can make it more

et al., 2018), authors introduced "MaeSTrO," a novel mobile application that facilitates a creative and localized style transfer editing process. Beyond social communication, NST has been a precious assisted tool for painters and designers. Nowadays, NST can make it more convenient for a painter to create a digital artwork of a particular style. Moreover, NST algorithms have produced a large panel of ready- to- use fashion components in various styles. This has immensely improved the efficiency of fashion designers and stylized CAD drawings and significantly reduced manufacturing costs (Dubey et al., 2020). NST has also been applied in the digital entertainment sector, such as in video games, via automatically stylizing a video scene into a particular artistic style in real- time. In this convention, (Chen et al.,2018) proposed CartoonGAN, a Generative Adversarial Network (GAN) based framework, to transform photos of real- world scenes into cartoon- style images with unpaired and cartoon images for training. Another work by (Cao et al., 2018) proposed CariGANs, an unpaired GAN architecture for face to caricatures translation; the model explicitly represents the geometric exaggeration and appearance stylization.
appearance stylization.

<!-- image_size: width=1655, height=2339 --> Technically speaking, generating images in NST methods is not unique. It rather depends on the usage of the optimization process and its workflow within the NST architecture. With that, image generation in NST can be classified into 1) optimization- based methods (Li, C. et al., 2016), where the synthesized output is directly generated by optimizing the content and style loss functions within the feature space of the CNN model. This method is relatively slow but usually leads to a higher synthesized quality, 2) feed- forward methods (Chen et al., 2017) that allow the stylized output images to be generated by a single iteration, however, the output is restrained by those pretrained style images, and 3) arbitrary methods (Huang et al., 2017) that generate stylized outputs within a single iteration given arbitrary style images. Despite improving computation efficiency, Feed- forward and arbitrary methods often sacrifice the synthesized quality. Based on their style modeling, NST techniques can be classified into 1) statistics- based and patch- based methods (Sheng et al., 2018). The former aims to represent the image style via some statistics. In this convention, the Gram matrix is one of the first introduced and commonly used statistical metrics for NST; it computes the correlation between the various feature maps extracted at each layer of CNN. The

image style via some statistics. In this convention, the Gram matrix is one of the first introduced and commonly used statistical metrics for NST; it computes the correlation between the various feature maps extracted at each layer of CNN. The Gram matrix has been notably improved and extended by recent NST methods. For example, (Risser et al., 2017) found that the large difference in the means and variances of feature maps is not fully reflected in the Gram matrix; to handle this imbalance, the authors integrated the histogram and TV losses within the Gram matrix. Likewise, (Li, S. et al., 2017) integrated a Laplacian loss to preserve the detailed structures of the content image and eliminate the artifacts. Other popular statistics in NST use the mean and variance for style quantification. For instance, (Li, Y. et al., 2017) presented a feed forward NST via a direct matching of feature covariance of the extracted feature activations to a given style image. Similarly, (Huang et al., 2017) introduced a novel NST method that enables arbitrary style transfer in real- time via an adaptive instance normalization layer that aligns the mean and variance of the content features with those of the style features. Based on Markov Random Field (MRF) and CNNs, patch- based NST methods directly extract and match the local neural patches

adaptive instance normalization layer that aligns the mean and variance of the content features with those of the style features. Based on Markov Random Field (MRF) and CNNs, patch- based NST methods directly extract and match the local neural patches of the content and style images (Li, C. et al., 2016). In this concept, for each patch in the synthesized feature activation, a similar patch in the style activation is matched, and the style loss is calculated as the cumulative distances between those patches. Interestingly, patch and statistics- based NST methods have been combined as in the work of (Sheng et al., 2018) by firstly applying a whitening and coloring transformation to obtain aligned feature activations, on which a patch swapping transformation is then performed. Attentional- based NST has recently been proposed, which can also be regarded as patch- based style transfer. In this regard, (Park et al., 2019) and (Deng et al., 2020) introduced a style- attentional network to match the style features into the content features and a self- attention mechanism for multi- stroke style transfer respectively. As far as the evaluation of NST algorithms is considered, the process is not entirely straightforward and remains an open and crucial challenge. Essentially, two major evaluation methodologies can be employed in the field of NST: qualitative and quantitative (Wang Z.

far as the evaluation of NST algorithms is considered, the process is not entirely straightforward and remains an open and crucial challenge. Essentially, two major evaluation methodologies can be employed in the field of NST: qualitative and quantitative (Wang Z. et al., 2021). The former relies on the aesthetic judgments of observers, and its results are related to many factors (e.g., profiles of participants). In contrast, the quantitative evaluation focuses on specific metrics, which include time complexity, loss variation, etc. ## 3. Neural Style Transfer (NST) In this section, we detail a Neural Style Transfer (NST) model that is used explicitly for an artistic style. In this architecture, a pretrained VGG- 16 model on the ImageNet dataset is employed for the extraction of features representing the semantics of an image's content and its underlying style. ## 1) Image Content: In the following, we discuss the input image from a content point of view. The input image named \(\hat{x}\) is convolved with the set of existing filters in each of the CNN's layers. A layer \(l\) often includes \(N_{l} \in \mathbb{Z}^{+}\) distinct filters to extract the various semantics of the image's content, and \(N^{l}\) feature maps each of size \(M_{l} \in \mathbb{Z}^{+}\) to encode the pixel values. Hence, the output of each layer \(l\) can be represented in the form of

distinct filters to extract the various semantics of the image's content, and \(N^{l}\) feature maps each of size \(M_{l} \in \mathbb{Z}^{+}\) to encode the pixel values. Hence, the output of each layer \(l\) can be represented in the form of a matrix \(F_{l} \in \mathbb{R}^{N_{l} \times M_{l}}\) , with \(F_{ij}^{l}\) denoting the activation of the filter \(i\) at the position \(j\) of layer \(l\) . The elements of the activation matrix \(F_{l}\) can therefore be used to represent and subsequently extract the content of the input image \(\hat{x}\) . It is significant to mention that the activations in the shallow layers tend to focus on low- level pixel information, whereas the activations of deeper layers often overlook individual pixel values and instead capture high

<!-- image_size: width=1655, height=2339 --> level semantic information such as the presence of objects in scenes and global arrangements of objects and their relative position. Figure 1 illustrates the architecture of an NST. <center>Figure 1: Illustration of the process of Neural Style Transfer </center> As for the content loss function, let \(\hat{x}\) and \(\hat{y}\) be the original and generated image, respectively, and \(X^{l}, Y^{l}\) be their respective feature maps at layer \(l\) . The contribution \(C_{l}(\hat{x}, \hat{y})\) of each layer \(l\) to the total content loss can then be written as follows: \[C_{l}(\hat{x},\hat{y}) = \frac{1}{2}\sum_{l,j}(X_{l,j}^{l} - Y_{l,j}^{l})\] And the total content loss \(L_{content}(\hat{x}, \hat{y})\) between \(\hat{x}\) and \(\hat{y}\) is \[L_{content}(\hat{x},\hat{y}) = \frac{1}{2}\sum_{l = 0}^{L}\gamma_{l}G_{l}(\hat{x},\hat{y})\] Where \(\gamma_{l}\) is a hyperparameter orchestrating the contribution value of each layer \(l\) toward the content loss. An \(\gamma_{l}\) value equal to 0 indicates that the filter response is entirely omitted at that layer. ## 2) Image Style: The style of an image is hard to define but is usually irrelevant to the image's content and its contained objects. One might therefore employ statistical analysis across all the feature maps to numerically represent an image style. To do so, the correlations between the feature maps are examined based on the Gram Matrix \(G_{l} \in \mathbb{R}^{N_{l} \times N_{l}}\) , where \(G_{ij}^{l}\) is the inner product between the

all the feature maps to numerically represent an image style. To do so, the correlations between the feature maps are examined based on the Gram Matrix \(G_{l} \in \mathbb{R}^{N_{l} \times N_{l}}\) , where \(G_{ij}^{l}\) is the inner product between the vectorized form of feature maps in channel \(i\) and \(j\) at layer \(l\) . \[G_{ij}^{l} = \sum_{k}(F_{ik}^{l}F_{jk}^{l})\]

<!-- image_size: width=1655, height=2339 --> Considering the correlations between feature maps of all layers, the style of an image is computed while disregarding the information related to the content. To compute the style loss, let us consider the following: Let \(\hat{x}\) and \(\hat{y}\) be the original and generated images, respectively, and \(X^{l}\) and \(Y^{l}\) be their style representations at layer \(l\) . The contribution \(S_{l}(\hat{x},\hat{y})\) of a given layer \(l\) to the total style loss is: \[S_{l}(\hat{x},\hat{y}) = \frac{1}{4N_{l}^{2}M_{l}^{2}}\sum_{l,j}(X_{l j}^{l} - Y_{l j}^{l})^{2}\] Where \((N_{l}*M_{l})\) is the size of the filter at layer \(l\) Subsequently, the total style loss \(L_{style}(\hat{x},\hat{y})\) between \(\hat{x}\) and \(\hat{y}\) is: \[L_{style}(\hat{x},\hat{y}) = \sum_{l = 0}^{L}\delta_{l}S_{l}(\hat{x},\hat{y})\] Where \(\delta_{l}\) is a hyperparameter specifying the contribution of each layer to the total style loss. An \(\delta_{l}\) value equal to 0 reflects a total absence of the style information that can be extracted from layer \(l\) . ## 3) Style Transfer Algorithm In machine learning or deep learning architectures, the model parameters are optimized beforehand using an optimization technique such as Gradient Descent. As a result, a model with its optimized parameters is obtained whereby a new input can be processed. Oppositely, transferring the style of an image \(\hat{a}\) onto another image \(\hat{b}\) is accomplished in our architecture by repeatedly optimizing the pixel values of a newly constructed image,

its optimized parameters is obtained whereby a new input can be processed. Oppositely, transferring the style of an image \(\hat{a}\) onto another image \(\hat{b}\) is accomplished in our architecture by repeatedly optimizing the pixel values of a newly constructed image, \(\hat{c}\) , so that the style of \(\hat{c}\) matches the style of \(\hat{a}\) and its content duplicates the content of \(\hat{b}\) . Therefore, the concept of a "model" optimized a priori is absent in our usage of NST. Instead, a separate optimization process occurs every time a new input takes place in the network. More specifically, at the first stage of the process, a new image \(\hat{c}\) is initialized to some random noise. Afterwards, a joined loss function comprising the style loss \(L_{style}(\hat{c},\hat{a})\) and content loss \(L_{content}(\hat{c},\hat{b})\) is optimized. The total loss function is defined as follows: \[L_{total}(\hat{a},\hat{b},\hat{c}) = \alpha L_{content}(\hat{c},\hat{b}) + \beta L_{style}(\hat{c},\hat{a})\] Where \(\alpha\) and \(\beta \in \mathbb{Z}^{+}\) are hyperparameters specifying the contribution weights of the content and style toward the total loss. A large \(\alpha /\beta\) ratio indicates the content of the image \(\hat{b}\) is emphasized more in the constructed image \(\hat{c}\) while a small \(\alpha /\beta\) value allocates more effort to the style of \(\hat{c}\) . The first step in the algorithm is to extract the content and style feature maps. To do so, the style

in the constructed image \(\hat{c}\) while a small \(\alpha /\beta\) value allocates more effort to the style of \(\hat{c}\) . The first step in the algorithm is to extract the content and style feature maps. To do so, the style image \(\hat{a}\) is passed through the network, and its style representation \(A^{l}\) is computed across all layers using the Gram Matrix. Subsequently, the content image \(\hat{b}\) is passed through the network, and its content representation \(B^{l}\) at each layer is stored. Next, the constructed image \(\hat{c}\) , whose pixel values are randomly initialized, is passed through the network, and its style matrix \(G^{l}\) and content activations \(F^{l}\) are computed. At each layer involved in the style representation, the mean square errors between the two Gram Matrices \(G^{l}\) and \(A^{l}\) is computed for the sake of \(L_{style}(\hat{c},\hat{a})\) loss function. Additionally, the mean squared difference between \(F^{l}\) and \(B^{l}\) activations is computed for the sake of computing the loss \(L_{content}(\hat{c},\hat{b})\) . The total loss \(L_{total}(\hat{a},\hat{b},\hat{c})\) is then computed as a linear combination between the content \(L_{content}(\hat{c},\hat{b})\) , and the \(L_{style}(\hat{c},\hat{a})\) loss. Moreover, as in a Gradient Descent optimizer, the derivative of the total loss is computed with respect to the pixel values of \(\hat{c}\) and dynamically adjusted via back- propagation. The process is repeated until \(\hat{c}\) matches the style features of \(\hat{a}\)

as in a Gradient Descent optimizer, the derivative of the total loss is computed with respect to the pixel values of \(\hat{c}\) and dynamically adjusted via back- propagation. The process is repeated until \(\hat{c}\) matches the style features of \(\hat{a}\) and its content features match \(\hat{b}\) .

Novel Methods Toward Future Possibilities <center>Figure 2 This diagram outlines the artistic process, of "Plant First City" by Shannon Xiaotong Shi 施晓彤. A straightforward subversion of the NST tool by combining two "non-style" images to conceive of and create a novel urban environment. </center> This paper reflects on a collection of works by the author and collaborators that seek to subvert the intended use case of NST. Our process utilized NST built on VGG16 and subsequently VGG19 conceived by Oxford's Visual Geometry Group (VGG, 19 denoting the number of layers in the network). (Gatys et al 2016)(Hassan 2021) The technology is designed to apply the style from, for example, a famous painting such as "Starry Night" by Van Gough, and apply it to a base image such as a photo taken with your phone. Our unconventional approach to the process involves the intuition of the designer as a part of the style transfer and compositing process. We outline a use case for NST in the early design phase of an architectural project where the designer goes back and forth between the NST process and other inputs toward an optimized result which meets the subjective, intuitive exploratory criteria of the designer. Our process encourages the mis- use of the NST process through subverting the

the designer goes back and forth between the NST process and other inputs toward an optimized result which meets the subjective, intuitive exploratory criteria of the designer. Our process encourages the mis- use of the NST process through subverting the labeling mechanisms inherent to the NST process; encouraging a style image to be used as a base image and what may be considered a base image as a style, or in other cases we forgo the style all together and instead opt to only feed the system base images; starving the system for a style. We also encourage the compositing of multiple more traditional NST images into a single composition. After several NST exercises the design can then respond to the collected results in a collaging exercise to create outcomes that otherwise would have been impractical. (Fig. 2)

<!-- image_size: width=1655, height=2339 --> ## Neural Style Transfer (NST) Workflow for Novel Architectural Results <center>Typical Style Transfer use case </center> <center>Hybrid Intelligence through Hacking the NST Process </center> The aesthetic of an NST often approaches something akin to computational impressionism. (Lee 2019) This style inherently lends itself to the potential for an emotional response from a viewer. Paired with unexpected, uncanny, or emotionally vivid elements the compositions often approach the sublime. (Kant 1914) These results can then be taken by the designer as a prompt, for further speculation and development based on a set of constraints. Our process maintains that NST output commonly provides a small peek into a potential world. It is up to the designer to take the prompt further and develop what they see in the image. After the designers develop their interpretations and speculations as a more flushed out image; often literally expanding the frame and providing elements of scale and context, a more traditional modeling process can follow, with the outcomes moving from not possible to conceived and on to a navigable experience, and possibly built. Although, there are several developing technologies with increasing capabilities able to translate single images into 3D digital models. Exploring these tools will be at the heart of future work in this research. Several of the use cases of

possibly built. Although, there are several developing technologies with increasing capabilities able to translate single images into 3D digital models. Exploring these tools will be at the heart of future work in this research. Several of the use cases of NST within this framework have resulted in the output weighing significantly on the final outcomes of the architectural design project. Three of the architectural design studios that have used this process have ended with results which have been directly inspired by the early visioning produced with the designer and the NST process. In the spring of 2022 the author ran an architectural design studio with co- instructor David Vardy, where NST was a core aspect to the early design phase. Later in the semester the results were curated in the "Computational Impressionism 无极之地" exhibition at the Longxi Art Museum in Zeya, Zhejiang Province. (see Fig. 5)

<!-- image_size: width=1655, height=2339 --> <center>Figure 4 This figure shows other student processes examples from image selection through to virtual environment. </center> The students began by doing site research. collecting material samples, natural artifacts, photographs, etc. They also began processing the programmatic requirements, and in turn begin thinking about precedent projects. All of these inputs inform the subject matter input into the NST process. Yet with the distinct interest in subverting the style transfer in favor of a mixing of ideas, the outcomes demand new subjective interpretations of the original object, not allowing the observer (including the designer) to be passive about their experience viewing the outcome from the exercise. The outcomes of this superficial process generally lack scale and context. The designer is called to engage with the art. The original subject is often no longer readily recognizable. Instead, the designer must layer their own psychological imprint on the piece to interpret it. It is the opportunity of the designer to define both. As mentioned earlier this happens through an expanding of the frame to define elements such as horizon, orientation, scale, and provide some reference indicators. The results of all of these efforts are both inspiring and important in the development of hybrid intelligence within creative disciplines.

Imagination: a Pioneering Effort for Humanity Much of what drives design are performative aspects of the outcomes, yet if we are only driven by the utilitarian requirements, we will never allow ourselves the opportunity to imagine alternatives. By pushing beyond what is conceivable we enable new possibilities for the future.(Rhees 2009) This can be referred to as the development of possible futures. It is a significant part of guiding the future. Hybrid intelligent processes such as style transfer can play a key role in this and other problems humanity faces. This research project builds on the heritage of the digital studios pioneered by Bernard Tschumi, and before him the work of Syd Mead (1933- 2019), Lebbeus Woods (1940- 2012), Roger Dean (1944), and others. We see the legacy of the Columbia University digital studio effort going on to create such projects as the digital Guggenheim, New City, and has even influenced Hollywood world building see examples from Alex McDowell and the World Building Media Lab at the University of Southern California. Yet this

studio effort going on to create such projects as the digital Guggenheim, New City, and has even influenced Hollywood world building see examples from Alex McDowell and the World Building Media Lab at the University of Southern California. Yet this is not the only lineage of computation influencing the future of urban conceptions. We have seen, particularly in the last ten years, the influence of computational methods such as parametric, procedural, and machine learning work the possibilities of creativity to incorporate computation as a collaborator. Beyond those technical aspects driving creativity and innovation, there are other stirrings including more cultural ones such as the post- digital movement which has worked to flatten and colorize predominant conceptions of our future. One could argue that the digital screen is the ultimate flattening, and yet the digital screen offers so much in terms of dimensionality. The imagery produced together with the artist and the computer using NST arguably creates a new aesthetic, a new style entirely, obviously grounded in a strong foundation briefly explored above. Yet this aesthetic quite possibly may have been previously out of reach without computational collaboration. The work that this group has undertaken is inherently optimistic and is rooted in questions such as: What kind of a world would you like to exist in if some limitation was removed?

previously out of reach without computational collaboration. The work that this group has undertaken is inherently optimistic and is rooted in questions such as: What kind of a world would you like to exist in if some limitation was removed? What possible futures could embody more sustainable circumstances for humanity? What is the ideal community for an individual? For industry? For community? What elements are needed in order to cultivate the most conducive environments? What methods of digital representation are optimal for expressing these ideas? How can one question traditional typologies and outdated organizational systems for the benefit of humanity? How do diverse family structures, demographics, and living/working styles affect the city? Consider the work of Shannon Xiaotong Shi 施晓彤 with her work highlighted in Fig. 4 entitled Plant First City. In this work she considers the absurd possibility of a city where plants receive the primary and first consideration. What

<!-- image_size: width=1655, height=2339 --> would such a reality feel like? In her extra- planetary conception plants are the dominant species and in order to survive humans must live symbiotically. Even the conception of such a reality is quite intensive, let along the instantiation of it as a navigable environment, which is exactly what she was able to accomplish with her partner Luna Yuwen Wang 王宇文. (Xiaotong 2021) <center>Figure 6 This image was produced through a composite of NST outputs in preparation for Latika 叶心怡 Ye Xinyi’s work moving to modeling, animating and creating a navigable VR environment </center> Another example comes from the DigitalFutures workshop entitled “Hacking Machine Learning Style Transfer 早期设计中的机器学习工作流” (Steenblik et al 2020) The image in Fig. 6 above image by Latika can best be explained in the artist's own words: "In the concept of Archighram's instant city, an assembled and disassembled city is delivered... the tent is set on balloons, and balloons float above the object. Then [it all] moves on to The next location. Based on this concept, I created an instant city with a personal style. On the basis of the existing building, balloons and airships were added to create a movable building space. There is a huge energy production center in the center of the city, a few tall buildings on the

a personal style. On the basis of the existing building, balloons and airships were added to create a movable building space. There is a huge energy production center in the center of the city, a few tall buildings on the edge of the city, other uses of air space are balloons and airships, and the transportation system is also shifted to the air." Latika developed an environment obsessed with transitory architecture, something that many have dreamed of but few have realized. Of course this fabricated virtual environment is not built, but regardless this may be the fiction that inspires the next generation to do something truly historically altering, in the same way that the pacemaker was inspired by Frankenstein. Regardless, this effort by the artist has impacted if no one else, her future. Hopefully she will reflect on this part of her architectural training as she is considering her career path. Content creation is a growing sector with promise. Regardless, her ability to conceive of realities outside of conventional human conception has been enhanced, and her confidence entertaining computational collaborations has grown.

<!-- image_size: width=1655, height=2339 --> ## 6.Virtual Habitation <center>Figure 7 This is a frame taken from "Parkour in Mars City", an Unreal Engine simulation by Alex Guo Yupeng 郭玉鹏 and Ted Kaiyuan Feng 冯开元, based upon a series of NST compositions. (Yupeng Et al 2021) </center> The technologies necessary to create complex digital worlds using automated computational methods seems to still be an illusive matter. NST and related technologies by themselves fall short of being a creative force in 3D world building alone.(Zhang Et al 2020) Yet NST can be a part of a collaborative process with designers in order to directly inform and participate in "world building"(Young 2020) minimally for virtual spaces. As virtual spaces are not limited by the constraints outside of computational environments, the NST results can then be taken by the designer as a prompt, for further speculation and development based on a set of constraints. NST seems to allow designers/architects to envision realities outside of the constraints of currently understood physics. This allows those who experience the place to engage in potentially impossible phenomena under any other circumstances. For example the work highlighted in Fig. 7 again deals with an extra- planetary parkour experience designed around the divergence in gravitational properties between our own earth and what might be; elsewhere. These landscapes become a "digital shadow" of a physical landscape that has not yet been realized. These shadows have a life of their own outside of any physical reality. The ambition is that through these virtual prototypes we can iterate faster through possibilities toward a better future. ## 7.Conclusion We have explored some pedagogical case studies, strengthening the argument that this process can yield compelling results that inspire and demand questioning, and quite possibly yield unconventional approaches to real world problems. <!-- image_size: width=2200, height=1700 --> # COMMUNITY-LED DESIGN IDEATION WITH PROFESSOR STEENBLIK FOR ABC STEWART MONTESSORI SCHOOL <center>Easy Problem Solving (easyproblem solving.com). </center> When ABC Stewart approached R. Spencer Steenblik and the Indiana University J. Irwin Miller Architecture program in the fall of 2021, regarding the potential renovation or construction of a new facility, his students in the graduate program began their research. First and foremost, the students addressed the programmatic needs of the school and discussed initial expectations and goals. One of the main suggestions from the research was to utilize "design thinking" to encourage stakeholder engagement in the design process. ## Design Thinking is the practice of using iterative processes to understand users, define problems, prototype ideas, and test potential solutions. Design thinking aims to put the users experience and needs at the center of the process before exploring its feasibility and viability. Over the years, design thinking has become an industry standard in the innovation space, helping countless companies, communities, and individuals understand the problems they are facing. This process was popularized by the Stanford D School and well known design company IDEO. Both of these groups refined their processes and definitions over time, creating a whole category of research that aims to engage stakeholders in the act of design. Interestingly, Columbus, Indiana too has a rich

and well known design company IDEO. Both of these groups refined their processes and definitions over time, creating a whole category of research that aims to engage stakeholders in the act of design. Interestingly, Columbus, Indiana too has a rich history of inviting the community to be part of the design and implementation process for its many architecture projects. <center>Interaction Design Foundation (interaction-design.org). </center> ## TRADITIONAL DESIGN THINKING One of the best known frameworks for design thinking comes from the Stanford D School. Their strategy involves the steps in the graphic above. They place an emphasis on understanding the audience, honing in on key questions, brainstorming solutions, building representations of ideas, then testing the ideas against user feedback. Through continuous iteration throughout the process, the ideas and prototypes get refined and tested with the end users of the solution, ensuring the products and services stay rooted in human needs.

<!-- image_size: width=2200, height=1700 --> ## IDEO: CO-DESIGNING SCHOOLS TOOLKIT IDEO is a global design company that practices a concept called human- centered design. They use design- thinking to solve complex challenges and use a people- first approach to design solutions. In the fall of 2020, IDEO released the Co- Designing Schools Toolkit - a collection of activities, research, and frameworks, specifically designed to help local communities develop strategies for empowering educators to improve their schools. This toolkit guides learning in the research phase with the implementation of six steps. 1. Build team Consider who to engage in the research process. 2. Define Aspiration Articulate a shared vision that aims to achieve a meaningful learning environment for the students. 3. Know your students Shadow the students in their environment. 4. Start hacking Begin to workshop with stakeholders and co- design using insights from student observation. 5. Understand Impact Once research is finished, you can begin to forecast solutions that may be useful. 6. Showcase Celebrate the learned insights with the stakeholders and guide them in a better understanding of potential solutions to improving their schools. With the growth of Cummins Engine Co. and the rise of J. Irwin Miller as its CEO in the 1940s, Columbus began to focus more on the importance of architecture to invigorate the fabric of the city. Miller championed a strategy for growth and development that engaged the community throughout the process. This framework eventually became known as the Columbus Way. "The Columbus Way is a mindset that means staying ahead of problems, encouraging and supporting enlightened leadership, building for the future, investing in high standards, invoking participation by all elements of the community, expressing concern for those in need and maintaining good schools and educational institutions" (Tucker 4). <!-- image_size: width=1700, height=2200 --> ## 02 Site Model Exercise 02 Site Model ExerciseEach student will be building a contoured site model using the three axis Computer Numerically Controlled (CNC) Mill. This model will be used throughout the semester, so it is important that it is accurate and well crafted. You may consider creating additional inset pieces for specific design schemes. Your model will be at \(1^{\prime \prime} = 30^{\prime} - 0^{\prime \prime}\) (360 Scale Factor) and will be approximately \(22^{\prime \prime} \times 34^{\prime \prime}\) . The Montessori way encourages the use of natural materials, so please consider this in your model making efforts. ## 03 Massing Model Exercise 03 Massing Model ExerciseYou will begin by taking the knowledge of the program that you have developed during the research exercise and apply it in developing massing models. You will begin the process by using foam to develop your schemes on the site. As we conclude the exercise you will finalize three schemes using wood. ## 04 Drawing Workshop with T.Kelly Wilson 04 Drawing Workshop with T. Kelly WilsonPlease be prepared for an intensive Space Exploration Workshop with Kelly. This will be a week long exercise where you will be working closely with Kelly to move through this visioning exercise. Students should be prepared to be in studio as much as

for an intensive Space Exploration Workshop with Kelly. This will be a week long exercise where you will be working closely with Kelly to move through this visioning exercise. Students should be prepared to be in studio as much as possible outside of class time during this week in order to fully take advantage of the workshoping method developed and executed by Kelly throughout the world. ## 05 Neural Style Transfer Exercise 05 Neural Style Transfer ExerciseThe Neural Style Transfer (NST) Exercise is meant to be, along with the Kelly Wilson Drawing Workshop, a disruptor, in order to free our minds of conventional expectations. Using sketches, drawings, model and site photographs, research and other inspiration imagery please begin exploring the essence of the project through a series of collages. We encourage the use of the machine learning NST technique as a part of your process. In class tutorials will be given on how best to utilize these tools for optimal outcomes, but most of the style transfer tools request a style and a content image to apply the style to. Our recommendations are that you attempt to subvert the designated inputs (style and content images) which allows for unexpected or uncanny results. NST is most productive in this use case when it is interpreted by the designer as a collaborative

Our recommendations are that you attempt to subvert the designated inputs (style and content images) which allows for unexpected or uncanny results. NST is most productive in this use case when it is interpreted by the designer as a collaborative process. The best initial results will not have ambiguities in scale and context. Both of these should be defined by the designer. Often this can be accomplished through combining several style transfers with a similar language as a collage. It is important to keep the selected input images and the output image for a full record of the process. Additionally, please cite all of the source images in an effort to be clear about authorship and to avoid taking credit for other's work. You will be expected to produce a minimum of 27 collages with elements of scale and context ensuring full and rich compositions. In the end you will select 9 collages as final products.
